{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti (also known as the *Manusmṛti*) Chapter 7, Manu describes `Daṇḍa`—the \"rod of punishment\"—as a divine embodiment of *Dharma* created by the primordial Lord to protect all beings (verses 14–18).**[^1]\n\n**The text explicitly elevates `Daṇḍa` above the king by portraying it as an independent, supremely powerful force: the king is merely its *wielder* (verse 26), and a corrupt king is destroyed by `Daṇḍa` itself (verses 27–28).**[^2][^3]\n\n> A king who wields it rightly prospers in the three goals; but one who is lustful, perverse, and base **is destroyed by `Daṇḍa` itself.** // Mn_7.27 //[^2]  \n> **For `Daṇḍa` is of great splendor, and difficult to wield by those of unpurified soul; it destroys a king who has swerved from Dharma,** along with his kinsmen. // Mn_7.28 //[^3]\n\n**This subordination of the king to `Daṇḍa` underscores its role as the ultimate guarantor of order, even over the ruler.**[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 7, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-73f910).  \n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 7, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-e9e861).  \n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 7, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-2d8a4d).  \n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 7, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-48dedc).",
